tion. He also considers the effects of judicial specialization on the work of the courts by demonstrating that under certain conditions, specialization can and does have fundamental effects on the policies that courts make. For this reason, the movement toward greater specialization constitutes a major change in the judiciary.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCourtszUnited States. 0aJudgeszUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aeconomics, government, private sector, criminal law, national security, foreign policy, judicial specialization, legal system, judges, judiciary, politics, political science, removal court, surveillance, intelligence, military justice, overseas courts, progressive era, sanctions, efficiency, litigation, regulation, revenue, expenditures, bankruptcy, business, corporate governance, patents, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226039565423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226039565/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles